Core requirements

1. Source restriction and ingestion
- Only accept source content from `https://www.ebanglalibrary.com/`.
- Accept these input types from UI and/or API:
  - direct `ebanglalibrary.com` book URLs
  - book titles/names that must be resolved to a valid `ebanglalibrary.com` book URL
- Support bulk import via:
  - pasted multiline URLs
  - pasted multiline titles
  - CSV upload
- Build a title-to-URL resolution flow for `ebanglalibrary.com`:
  - normalize Bengali/English punctuation and spacing
  - reuse the repository's existing normalization/fuzzy-matching ideas where helpful
  - crawl or index the relevant `ebanglalibrary` catalog/discovery pages as needed
  - resolve to the best candidate source URL
  - store both the original submitted title and the resolved source URL
  - when there is no confident exact match, show up to 3 closest candidate books with enough context for the user to choose
  - require explicit user confirmation before using a fuzzy match
  - if the user does not confirm, keep the submission pending review instead of guessing silently
- Reject or flag inputs that resolve outside `ebanglalibrary.com`.
- Every accepted submission attempt must be stored with:
  - submitter identity
  - original input
  - resolved URL if any
  - match confidence / resolution status
  - timestamps
  - processing status
  - audit trail
- If a submission matches an existing book, do not silently discard it. Preserve the submission and link it to the existing book where appropriate.

2. Metadata extraction and normalization
- Reuse and improve the current repository logic for extracting:
  - book title
  - author/writer
  - translator
  - editor
  - category/type/genre
  - series
  - cover image
  - book info / front-matter block
  - dedication
  - TOC and content items
- When source metadata contains comma-separated values for writers/authors, translators, editors, series, categories, or types, do not keep the combined comma-joined string as the canonical database value.
- Split comma-separated metadata into separate normalized items and save each item as its own record in the appropriate table/relationship.
- Preserve the original raw scraped string for provenance and review, but the canonical relational model must use separate linked records.
- Because the current scraper often returns author/series/type as flat strings, introduce a normalization layer that converts current scraper output into canonical structured records before persistence and before rendering/export steps that still need display-friendly strings.
- Preserve the current ability to build both HTML and EPUB outputs.
- Implement a deterministic metadata extraction pipeline first.
- Store raw snippets/provenance so later AI-assisted extraction can be layered in without redesign.
- Extracted metadata must remain editable and reviewable by authorized users.

3. Data model and persistence
- Use a relational schema with at least:
  - books
  - book submissions
  - title resolution attempts / match candidates
  - source URLs
  - contributors/people
  - contributor roles
  - book contributors
  - series
  - book-series relationships
  - categories/types
  - book-category/type relationships
  - generated assets
  - processing jobs/logs
  - users
  - role bundles / permission grants
  - per-book access rules
  - audit logs
  - metadata review states
  - metadata version history
  - duplicate review / merge records
  - preview/read access sessions or tokens
  - reading progress / reading sessions if reader state is supported
  - bookmarks if reader state is supported
- Support many-to-many relationships for contributors, series, and categories/types.
- Writers/authors, translators/editors, series, and categories/types must be normalized as separate records and relationships, not stored canonically as one comma-separated text field.
- Keep raw scraped values for provenance, but store the canonical structured metadata in relational form.
- Store contributor role labels explicitly instead of as raw free text only.
- Support record states such as:
  - draft
  - processing
  - needs review
  - ready
  - published
  - archived
  - soft deleted

4. Background processing
- Move long-running scraping and generation into background jobs.
- Support statuses such as:
  - queued
  - processing
  - succeeded
  - failed
- Preserve failure details and retry history.
- Provide a dashboard or queue view for:
  - job state
  - retries
  - error details
  - linked submission/book

5. Duplicate handling and review
- Implement duplicate detection using:
  - exact source URL matching
  - normalized metadata matching where reasonable
- Provide workflows for:
  - duplicate review
  - duplicate merge
  - title-resolution review
- Never silently guess when ambiguity is material.

6. Search, filtering, and discovery
- Add search/filtering for:
  - book title
  - submitted title/query
  - author
  - category/type
  - series
  - creation date
  - processing status
  - submission status
  - review status
- Searches and filters for authors, series, and categories/types should operate on the normalized related records, not only on raw comma-joined scraped strings.
- Provide usable sorting and saved filters.
- Use slug-based book URLs where appropriate.
- Make the library feel like a real catalog, not a table dump.

7. Public vs protected behavior
- Broad submission should be supported, but durable access must remain controlled.
- The creator of a submission is not automatically entitled to permanent read/download access unless policy grants it.
- A newly created/generated book may support a short-lived preview/read flow tied to that submission or result session.
- Repeated reading/reopening and downloading must require proper authorization.
- Submission endpoints must still be protected with validation, rate limits, and audit logging.

8. Authentication and authorization
- Use email + password authentication.
- Support password reset by email.
- Support TOTP-based 2FA.
- Seed or initialize `rsalehin24@gmail.com` as the super admin account, without hardcoding unsafe credentials.
- Support self-service user creation/signup if needed for the broad submission model.
- Implement proper authentication and authorization between the React frontend and Django backend.
- Backend authorization is mandatory for:
  - protected APIs
  - file downloads
  - reader launch flows
  - book-management actions
  - permission-management actions
- Frontend route guards are useful for UX but are never sufficient for security.
- Prefer a production-ready React + Django auth model such as secure HttpOnly session cookies with CSRF protection, unless another approach is clearly justified.
- If frontend and backend are served from different origins/subdomains, configure CSRF/CORS/origin handling safely and explicitly.
- The frontend must have a reliable way to fetch:
  - current user
  - session state
  - 2FA state
  - permission scopes/capabilities
- Handle `401` and `403` cleanly in the frontend.
- Model permissions so users can hold multiple grants at once.
- Support action-level permissions such as:
  - submit/create
  - preview/read once
  - durable read/reopen
  - download
  - edit metadata
  - manage processing
  - manage access
  - admin/full control

9. EPUB output, download, and reader integration
- Continue generating EPUB files from the refactored services.
- After successful EPUB generation, show clear result actions:
  - `Download`
  - `Download and View`
- For multiple generated books, support bulk actions.
- If the user chooses `Download and View`, initiate the authorized download flow and open the reader for authorized books.
- The reader launch must integrate with the deployed reader site `https://ereader.rsalehin24.me/`.
- If the local reader codebase exists at `/Users/rsalehin24/Documents/epub-reader`, implement the reader-side changes there too when needed.
- When multiple books are opened for viewing, open them in separate tabs as part of a direct user-initiated action.
- Protect the reader launch with backend validation and short-lived signed access or equivalent secure server-side validation.
- Do not rely only on client-side checks.
- Persist reading state if feasible:
  - reading progress
  - last opened location
  - bookmarks
- If reader-side implementation is blocked because the reader code is unavailable or incompatible, document the exact integration contract and required changes.

